In this (what I would say was fun) session, I realized that my stand only worked if the phone was at a 90 degree angle, but I many times like my phone to be at a 60 or 45 degree angle! So after about 10 minutes of thinking of ways to do this (Whether it can rotate or just whether it doesn't even matter- perhaps my stand does work for any angle) I landed on this idea: My stand can be broken up into different lengths (each has a magnet so they can connect togther when they want to become larger) and instead of the stand being what it was (image below):

{A5247F0A-72A1-47A6-9827-D4F767A85DF4}

The rectangular prism at the top would be part of the case (super-glued) and the slanted one would connect by magent. But after I thought more, I realized that the rectangular prism would be pretty much useless. Instead, I could just add magnets to the case itself! Here is what the new stand would look like:

{E1F50719-6338-49E3-BFB4-2B8951DA1E86}

Next, I wanted to split up the stand to see if it would even work. I imagined it would, so I split the stand up in 4 parts. Here is where I hit a rabbit hole. when I split it, the only degrees was 0 and 90. I couldn't get it between, so I knew that this technique wouldn't work.

After a good 10 minutes of thoughts, I though about making magnets that go top to bottom (3). The stand would be the length of the one closest to the bottom, and as you go up, the angle would get closer to 0. There are 3 different angles on this version, and it may not be very sturdy, so another 3d print would allow the figure to keep balance. This is the final model, and I am now done with the phone case model!

Note that when I will begin the building process, I will first only print the actual case, then print the fun accesories such as the github cat head, and the stand +magnets.

{A0A6A23E-54E0-475A-A125-737C11387E8B}

So to sumarize, I made an improved stand version and pretty much finished my design. All that's left is to get building :) Yay! 
